node.text:
PLUM BITES

When plums are in season this is a nice healthy recipe to make...very delicious and also will satisfy your sweet cravings. 
Plums are amongst the antioxidants richest foods and when coupled with power packed seeds... the combination is lethal?
An interesting makeover of the very popular 'Granola'.. 

Ingredients ?
Filling:
Plums -5 (seeds removed and chopped) 
2 tbsp honey

Base:
1 cup rolled oats
1/4 cup almonds sliced
1/4 cup walnuts
1tbsp honey
2 tsp olive oil
1 tsp cinnamon powder 
Sea salt - pinch

Toppings:
Rolled oats- 1 tbsp
Pumpkin seeds-2tsp
Sunflower seeds-1 tsp
Flax seeds-1tsp
Dried cranberries- 8-10
1 tsp Olive oil

Procedure
1. In a heated pan,  add chopped plums with honey and cook for 10 mins to make plum compote. 
2. In a blender add the ingredients for base and mix to form a powder. Press it along the tart tin and bake at 180deg C for 15 min. 
3. Once the base cools down, spread the plum compote, sprinkle the toppings, press it slightly and bake again for 20 min. 
4. Demould the tin, cut into triangles and serve.

Eagerly awaiting the announcement from our 1st minister that we can reopen in Wales ??????? 

I know I keep going on about it, but it has been the longest wait ever. I’m over the moon for my colleagues in England and wish them all the best as they prepare to reopen on the 1st August.

.By Taylor Borman
There is a good reason why Forearm Plank is incorporated in every Yoga Pod class — it fires you up!
Benefits
One of the beautiful things about yoga is the opportunity to allow your body to discover. When choosing an ab exercise, you really can’t go wrong with Forearm Planks. They are a functional movement that trains the abs to support the spine in day-to-day activities. If you are looking for a pose that soothes the chaos, brings a greater sense of concentration, and pushes you to live your intentions off the mat, then Forearm Plank is just what you need.
Let’s talk about the physical benefits of this pose. After all, a sustainable yoga practice should have a healthy balance of mindfulness and physical activity. Although it’s tough, when done correctly, the Forearm Plank strengthens the abs, legs and core. It is also good for stretching the arches of your feet as well as your calves, shoulders and hamstrings.

node.text: Livia Marin is a London-based Chilean artist whose work has been characterized throughout by large-scale installations and the appropriation of mass-produced and mass-consumed objects.She employs everyday objects to enquire into the nature of how we relate to material objects in an era dominated by standardization and global circulation. In this, the work seeks to offer a reflection on the relationship we develop with those often-unseen objects that meet our daily needs. Central to the work is a troupe of estrangement that works to reverse an excess of familiarity that commands the life of the everyday and the dictates of the marketplace. Marin has exhibited widely both in her native Chile and internationally.

Photo by Simar Malhotra on July 23, 2020. Image may contain: text that says 'Our eye-brows don't need that bi-monthly grooming we thought they they did. Not having to match up to foisted beauty standard is liberating and perhaps, just allowing ourselves to be, without judgement, is what we needed to find beauty in us in the first place.'

Photo by Simar Malhotra on July 23, 2020. Image may contain: text that says 'Our urges to buy and consume are a lot greater than our needs. And once those urges stop finding an outlet, gradually, the wants reduce.'

Photo by Simar Malhotra on July 23, 2020. Image may contain: text that says 'Our own company isn't all that terrible. After the initial spurt of cribbing and complaining about the ockdown, of not being able to live life in the way that we did, the mind and body slowly get accustomed to what they'r offered. There is a weird comfort in watching films and reading and making art, by ourselves, for ourselves, which we might not have known otherwise.'

Photo by Simar Malhotra on July 23, 2020. Image may contain: text that says 'We are stronger, more resilient than we think. Whether it's friendships, our relationships, our work, our exercise routine, our food habits. Even in desperate, unprecedented situations, in which we're quite literally stuck, and sometimes stranded, we might not have thrived, but we've made things work.'

Photo by Simar Malhotra on July 23, 2020. Image may contain: text that says 'We are malleable, and our minds agile. Irrespective of our age, this pandemic has opened doors for us, allowed to explore. Whether it's perfecting efficient crockery washing, learning how bake up our own pita, introducing Zoom into our social life at 80, earning that Photoshop certificate or emotionally navigating the lockdown, we have learned. And we can give ourselves the credit for that.'

Photo by Simar Malhotra on July 23, 2020. Image may contain: text that says 'Gratitude is key. This pandemic has proven to us that we have so much to be grateful for. And if you haven't been grateful yet, then take that that second right now.'

node.text: Restless. Trying to sit down to get some DBT work done but I’m itchy to move. To get out. To go away. This house is too small. I wish my family would go away for a while, or that I could go away for a while. Lockdown is really hard to get through for a second time. I really miss the time that they were at work or I was out, where I had a few hours away from them. How does everyone else cope? There has to be something that would help that I’ve yet to think of. #covid19 #covid_19 #covid #coronavirus #pandemic #lockdown #lockdown2020 #lockdownlife #lockdowndiaries #lockdownsessions #anxiety #anxietyrelief #anxietyawareness #anxietysupport #anxietyproblems #anxious #anxiousmind #struggle #struggleisreal #struggling #struggling #struggles #mentalhealth #mentalhealthawareness #mentalhealthmatters #mentalhealthmonth #mentalhealthrecovery #mentalhealthblogger #mentalhealthadvocate #mentalhealthsupport

- Reporting from day 128 of #WorkFromHome and #Isolation! I was a very, good girl during the first 3 months of #Lockdown and then mid June hit, I lost all my nerve but mostly because I saved up and brought these 13 beauties during July and July. Nearly half of these are pre-loved and the other half is new paperbacks. And I am soooooo looking forward to a quick break over the Eid Holidays and devour some of these. Here's hoping our trials end post Eid-ul-Adha! AAMEEN, SUMAAMEEN.

node.text:
Finally felt right to post something.
I don't have a big caption related to this one click, as I just captured it one day while roaming with friends looking for an ice-cream shop (you know who you are ?).
This time of pandemic has been tough for a majority of people, as it has affected their livelihoods, directly or indirectly.
I just want to say Hang in there! I hope we all are able to fight this with unity and a clear goal of following precautions.
As far as I am concerned, it gives me a reason to explain WHY am I sitting jobless and with no work at home.
Also, to all final year student's like me, don't lose hope and have a little bit more patience. I hope things go smoothly.
And one more thing, I never followed my *summer goals* so this year was actually a relief in that sense ??

node.text:
This was 2.5 years ago when my 2 hernias never existed in my life.Workout used to be heavy weights and abs and cardio everyday for 2.5hrs.I was a newbie to the gym and was very much eager in lifting heavy and adding more lean muscle day by day and I always worked out using all pre and post  precautions and maintaining posture .Few months later I was diagnosed with right inguinal congenital hernia and had to undergo a surgery and three months later while I started working out slowly again I developed pain on the other side and on visiting the doctor I was diagnosed with a similar hernia on the other side which was mild and had to undergo severe rehab to prevent surgery but it's been years and I'm doing my rehab to prevent surgery and not picking up heavy weights and working out in a simple manner without weights .I don't want to undergo surgeries any more and just want my body to adapt and learn from it as my body becomes weaker everytime I undergo a surgery and also it isn't so severe .So since then till now I have made a good connection with my mind and body and apply what works for me best .For me bodybuilding isn't the goal .All I ever wanted was to be fit and get fitter day by day .Now,I am not supposed to lift heavy but still managing to improve my strength using bodyweight calisthenics workout.Nothing can stop me.Going to keep grinding 
LIGHT WEIGHT BABY?

node.text: Life so brilliantly depicted here Robert. I love and admire the fact that you’re creating a new story even though it’s hard. I hope you’ll keep sharing it as you go...
I'd love to know if you find a story.
@esmiems well, I have some ideas, but as of now they’re all still not very good ones

I really liked this post, thank you. It sounds very familiar. Lockdown was hard for lots of reasons obviously but it was also very straightforward if you weren't someone that had to go out which made it easy to do the Right Things, but now it's all messy and confusing and different and exhausting in very different ways.
I'd love to know if you find a story.
@esmiems well, I have some ideas, but as of now they’re all still not very good ones

I was thinking this week that for me one of the hard things about the pandemic has also been one that's difficult about depression— it's very tempting to imagine a kind of narrative arc to it where it's really hard, but then everything gets better, and then that doesn't happen and that makes things harder than they were.

I know I thought that lockdown easing would be nice. And it has been nice! But it's also involved things like visiting shops I've not been to for months and seeing them full of cordons and plastic shields; seeing the difference for the first time is always more difficult than watching things gradually change. Things like being surrounded by families in the park who are trying to pretend that they're having fun. They were looking forward to having fun, their eyes all say. They don't know what to do now it's miserable here as well.

I know a lot of people have found this time hard, much harder than they thought they would. And they don't know how to say it's been hard because it wasn't supposed to be hard, and being unhappy is always harder when you're somewhere that's meant to be nice. At times like this I often think I need to tell myself a new story that can cope with how messy my actual life and feelings are. I'm not sure I've thought of one quite yet. But I think it's important to admit that I'm trying to find one, rather than to pretend the one I had is working especially well.
